Data Sources and Method overview

In this notebook we combine three data sources to produce a long-term time-series of government health expenditure as a share of GDP. The figure, taken from âthe OECDâs public funding for health care brief (2020)â, below shows public and private funding contribute to health care goods and services. The section we focus on in this notebook is highlighted in the grey boxes, expenditure which is either government schemes, social health insurance or compulsory health insurance.

The data sources we use are Lindert (1994), OECD (1993), OECD Stat and were combined as follows:

For the period 1970-2020 we report the figures as published in OECD Stat. For the period 1960-1969, we extended the recent figures (from OECD Stat) backwards by using the rates of change as reported in OECD (1993). For the period 1880-1930, we report observations from Lindert (1994).

To be precise, the process of extrapolation consisted in taking the earliest available observation from OECD Stat (A), and then successively extending the series backwards; by using the year-by-year rate of change implied by the estimates in OECD 1993 (B), for the period 1960-1969. Here is an example:

\[A_{t-1}= A_t * (B_{t-1}/A_t)\]

We use backward extrapolation because it is not possible to splice the estimates from OECD Stat and OECD (1993). This is because, while the trends are consistent, there are differences in levels due to changes in definitions and measurement.â

library(tidyr)

Download the data

We download the data from OECD Stat - the data is available here. If we already have downloaded a version of the data from the current year then we use that, if not a new version is downloaded.

Code 
year <- format(Sys.Date(),"%Y")
oecd_stat_fp <- paste0("data/oecd_stat_",year,".csv")
download.file('https://stats.oecd.org/sdmx-json/data/DP_LIVE/.HEALTHEXP.../OECD?contentType=csv&detail=code&separator=comma&csv-lang=en', oecd_stat_fp )

Standardise the countries

Loading in the country standardisation csv:

Code 
countries <- read.csv("data/country_names_country_standardized.csv") %>% distinct()

Loading and plotting the OECD Stat data

Reading in the data downloaded from OECD Stat. We are using the values relating to âGovernment/Compulsoryâ expenditure - which is here coded âCOMPULSORYâ in the âSUBJECTâ column.

In this code chunk we also standardise the country names to OWID country names.

We also add rows so that for each country every year between the first and last has its own row.

Code 
oecd <- read.csv(oecd_stat_fp) %>% filter(SUBJECT == 'COMPULSORY' & MEASURE == 'PC_GDP') %>%
  select(entity = LOCATION, year = TIME,value = Value ) %>% 
  mutate(source = 'oecd_stat')%>% 
  left_join(., countries, by = c('entity'= 'Country')) %>% 
  select(entity = Our.World.In.Data.Name, year, value, source)%>% 
  group_by(entity) %>% 
  tidyr::complete(year = full_seq(min(year):max(year), 1))

ggplot()+
  geom_line(data =oecd, aes(x = year, y = value, group = interaction(entity)))+
  labs(x = "Year", y= "Government Health Expenditure (%GDP)")+
  facet_wrap(.~entity)+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(1970, 2020, 25))+
  theme_bw()

Reading in the data from OECD 1993, which is available here.

In this code chunk we also standardise the country names to OWID country names and filter out countries that arenât in the OECD stat dataset.

ggplot()+

###Â Linearly interpolating missing data Here we linearly interpolate missing data from both OECD datasets. For example the data for France between is only available every five years between 1970 and 1990, so we interpolate the missing values.

Code 
oecd <- oecd %>% group_by(entity) %>%
  mutate(value = na.approx(value, na.rm = FALSE)) %>%
  ungroup()

oecd_93 <- oecd_93 %>% group_by(entity) %>%
  mutate(value = na.approx(value, na.rm = FALSE)) %>%
  ungroup()

Combine the OECD datasets and plot the combined data

Here we combine both the datasets and plot them, coloured according to the source. Values which have been linearly interpolated (as described above) are shown as âOWID_estimateâ.

Code 
oecd_both<- rbind(oecd, oecd_93) 
oecd_both$source[is.na(oecd_both$source)] <- 'OWID_estimate'
ggplot()+
  geom_point(data =oecd_both %>% filter(entity %in%c('France', 'Germany')), aes(x = year, y = value, group = interaction(source,entity), colour = source), size = 1)+

  labs(x = "Year", y= "Public/Government Health Expenditure (%GDP)")+
  facet_wrap(.~ entity)

Calculating the rate of change in OECD Stat data

Calculating the rate of change in the OECD Stat data. Here we create a new column (time_m1) which is lagged by one year, for example values in the âvalueâ column for 1971 rows are shown as 1972 in the âtime_m1â column.

We then the divide the âtime_m1â column by the âvalueâ column to estimate the rate of change - in a backwards direction. So we would estimate the rate of change from 1972 to 1971.

Code 
roc_df<- oecd %>% 
  select(entity, year, value) %>% 
  group_by(entity) %>% 
  arrange(entity,year) %>% 
  mutate(time_m1 = lag(value, n = 1L), br_roc = time_m1/value, source = 'oecd_stat') %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  filter(complete.cases(.))

Calculating the rate of change in OECD 1993 data

Calculating the rate of change in the OECD 1993 data. Here we create a new column (time_m1) which is lagged by one year, for example values in the âvalueâ column for 1971 rows are shown as 1972 in the âtime_m1â column.

We then the divide the âtime_m1â column by the âvalueâ column to estimate the rate of change - in a backwards direction. So we would estimate the rate of change from 1972 to 1971.

oecd_93_roc <- oecd_93 %>%

Interpolating missing rates of change

  group_by(entity) %>%

###Â Applying the rates of change to the OECD datasets

This loop iterates through each entity and within this iterates through each year (going backwards through time), to multiply the current âvalueâ by the current âbr_rocâ (rate of change) to calculate the âvalueâ for the next year.

The calculations for each entity are combined as the loop runs.

Code 
oecd_out <- oecd %>%
  select(entity, year, value)
oecd_loop <- NULL
entities <- unique(oecd_out$entity)
for (entity_sel in entities) {
  oecd_sel <- oecd_out %>%
    filter(entity == entity_sel)
  start_reg_year <- min(oecd_sel$year)
  min_roc_year <-
    roc_int %>% group_by(entity) %>%  filter(entity == entity_sel, year == min(year)) %>% ungroup() %>% select(year)  %>% pull()
  
  if (length(min_roc_year)  == 1) {
    if (min_roc_year <= start_reg_year) {
      years <- start_reg_year:min_roc_year
      for (year_sel in years) {
        roc_yr <-
          roc_int %>% filter(year == year_sel & entity == entity_sel)
        
        oecd_new <- oecd_sel %>% filter(year == year_sel) %>%
          mutate(value = value * roc_yr$br_roc, year = year_sel - 1) %>%
          select(entity, year, value)
        
        oecd_sel <- rbind(oecd_sel, oecd_new)
        
      }
    }
  }
  oecd_loop <- rbind(oecd_loop, oecd_sel)
}

Adding Lindert data

Lastly, we add in the Lindert data.

Code 
full_owid <- rbind(oecd_loop, lindert %>% select(-source))
full_owid <- full_owid %>% select(entity, year, public_health_expenditure_pc_gdp = value) %>% filter(complete.cases(.))

full_owid$source <- 'OWID_estimate'

  geom_line(data =oecd_both%>% filter(entity %in% lindert$entity), aes(x = year, y = value, group = interaction(source,entity), colour = source))+

### Data Sources and Method overview

In this notebook we combine three data sources to produce a long-term time-series of government health expenditure as a share of GDP. The figure, taken from ['the OECD's public funding for health care brief (2020)'](https://www.oecd.org/health/Public-funding-of-health-care-Brief-2020.pdf), below shows public and private funding contribute to health care goods and services. The section we focus on in this notebook is highlighted in the grey boxes, expenditure which is either government schemes, social health insurance or compulsory health insurance. 

![Figure from 'Public funding for health care brief (OECD,2020)'](OECD-brief.png)


The data sources we use are [Lindert (1994)](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1YFlIC-on7oWiDhgdETUD9PSVE-BTaySn/view?usp=sharing), [OECD (1993)](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Xa9WRtQq_Dfeod8mfJzcj6TGXak7APRF/view?usp=sharing.), [OECD Stat](https://stats.oecd.org/sdmx-json/data/DP_LIVE/.HEALTHEXP.../OECD?contentType=csv&detail=code&separator=comma&csv-lang=en) and were combined as follows:

For the period 1970-2020 we report the figures as published in OECD Stat.
For the period 1960-1969, we extended the recent figures (from OECD Stat) backwards by using the rates of change as reported in OECD (1993). 
For the period 1880-1930, we report observations from Lindert (1994).

To be precise, the process of extrapolation consisted in taking the earliest available observation from OECD Stat (_A_), and then successively extending the series backwards; by using the year-by-year rate of change implied by the estimates in OECD 1993 (_B_), for the period 1960-1969. Here is an example:

$$A_{t-1}= A_t * (B_{t-1}/A_t)$$

We use backward extrapolation because it is not possible to splice the estimates from OECD Stat and OECD (1993). This is because, while the trends are consistent, there are differences in levels due to changes in definitions and measurement."

```{r}
  start_reg_year <- min(oecd_sel$year)
  min_roc_year <-
    roc_int %>% group_by(entity) %>%  filter(entity == entity_sel, year == min(year)) %>% ungroup() %>% select(year)  %>% pull()
  
  if (length(min_roc_year)  == 1) {
    if (min_roc_year <= start_reg_year) {
      years <- start_reg_year:min_roc_year
      for (year_sel in years) {
        roc_yr <-
          roc_int %>% filter(year == year_sel & entity == entity_sel)
        
        oecd_new <- oecd_sel %>% filter(year == year_sel) %>%
          mutate(value = value * roc_yr$br_roc, year = year_sel - 1) %>%
          select(entity, year, value)
        
        oecd_sel <- rbind(oecd_sel, oecd_new)
        
      }
    }
  }
  oecd_loop <- rbind(oecd_loop, oecd_sel)
}

```

### Adding Lindert data

Lastly, we add in the Lindert data.
```{r}
full_owid <- rbind(oecd_loop, lindert %>% select(-source))
full_owid <- full_owid %>% select(entity, year, public_health_expenditure_pc_gdp = value) %>% filter(complete.cases(.))

full_owid$source <- 'OWID_estimate'
```
